---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
---
<DocsLayout
  title="Docker Swarm"
  description="Deploy to a Docker Swarm cluster with native rolling updates, convergence polling, and automatic rollback detection."
  section="strategies"
>
  <p>
    The swarm strategy delegates orchestration to Docker Swarm. Shuttle initializes the swarm if
    needed, generates a <code>docker-compose.swarm.yml</code>, runs <code>docker stack deploy</code>,
    and polls until all service tasks converge. Swarm handles replica scheduling, <code>start-first</code>
    rolling updates, and rollback detection natively.
  </p>
  <p>
    This strategy is ideal when you need multi-node horizontal scaling without an external registry
    (using <code>local-registry</code>) or with one (GHCR, Docker Hub).
  </p>

  <h2>8-step deploy pipeline</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Ensure Swarm is initialized</strong> — runs <code>docker info</code> to check swarm state. If not active, runs <code>docker swarm init --advertise-addr &lt;host&gt;</code> automatically.</li>
    <li><strong>Build &amp; distribute image</strong> — build locally and push to the configured registry. For single-node swarm use <code>local-transfer</code>. For multi-node use <code>local-registry</code> (ephemeral registry + SSH tunnel) or an external registry.</li>
    <li><strong>Upload secrets</strong> — push AES-encrypted secrets as <code>.env</code> to <code>/opt/shuttle/&lt;app&gt;/&lt;app&gt;/.env</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Generate &amp; upload compose file</strong> — renders <code>docker-compose.swarm.yml</code> with replica count, update policy, and env_file path; uploads to <code>/opt/shuttle/&lt;app&gt;/&lt;app&gt;/docker-compose.swarm.yml</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Deploy stack</strong> — runs <code>docker stack deploy -c &lt;composePath&gt; --with-registry-auth &lt;app&gt;</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Wait for convergence</strong> — polls <code>docker service inspect</code> every 5 seconds. Detects: <code>completed</code> (success), <code>rollback_completed</code> / <code>rollback_paused</code> (Swarm auto-rolled back), <code>paused</code> (update paused due to failure). Throws on any failure state.</li>
    <li><strong>Update proxy upstream</strong> — updates Caddy to point to the service's published port.</li>
    <li><strong>Write state</strong> — persists <code>state.json</code> with tag, port, and version.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Configuration</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">app: my-app
domain: my-app.example.com

server:
  host: 203.0.113.10
  user: deploy

build:
  dockerfile: Dockerfile

services:
  web:
    command: node server.js
    port: 3000

# Swarm-specific block
swarm:
  replicas: 3                   # number of task replicas
  update_parallelism: 1         # tasks to update at a time
  update_delay: 10s             # pause between each replica update
  update_order: start-first     # start new task before stopping old (zero-downtime)
  monitor: 15s                  # time to monitor new tasks before marking update successful
  convergence_timeout: 300      # seconds to wait for all tasks to converge

deploy:
  strategy: swarm

# Use local-registry for multi-node without external registry
registry:
  driver: local-registry

# Or GHCR for multi-node with external registry
# registry:
#   driver: ghcr
</code></pre>

  <h2>update_order: start-first</h2>
  <p>
    With <code>update_order: start-first</code> (the default), Swarm starts the new task and waits
    for it to reach the <em>Running</em> state before stopping the old one. This ensures no service
    interruption during rolling updates. The <code>monitor</code> window (default 15s) gives Swarm time
    to confirm the new task is healthy before moving to the next replica.
  </p>
  <p>
    <code>stop-first</code> is available but reduces availability: the old task stops before the new
    one starts, creating a brief gap. Only use it when you can't run two copies of the task
    simultaneously (e.g., due to port conflicts or exclusive resource locks).
  </p>

  <h2>Convergence polling and rollback detection</h2>
  <p>
    Shuttle polls <code>docker service inspect --format '&#123;&#123;.UpdateStatus.State&#125;&#125;'</code> every 5 seconds.
    The following states are handled:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>State</th>
        <th>Meaning</th>
        <th>Shuttle action</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>completed</code> or empty</td>
        <td>Update finished or no update in progress</td>
        <td>Verify all tasks Running, succeed</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>rollback_completed</code></td>
        <td>Swarm auto-rolled back to previous image</td>
        <td>Throw DeployError</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>rollback_paused</code></td>
        <td>Swarm rollback paused (manual intervention needed)</td>
        <td>Throw DeployError</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>paused</code></td>
        <td>Update paused due to task failure</td>
        <td>Throw DeployError</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    If convergence doesn't complete within <code>convergence_timeout</code> (default: 300s), Shuttle
    throws a timeout error. The Swarm stack is left in its current state for inspection.
  </p>

  <h2>HEALTHCHECK in Dockerfile is required</h2>
  <p>
    Swarm's <code>start-first</code> update order and monitor window rely on Docker's native
    HEALTHCHECK instruction to determine task health. Without a HEALTHCHECK, Swarm considers tasks
    healthy as soon as they start, which may allow a broken container to pass the monitor window.
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-dockerfile">FROM node:20-alpine
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN npm ci --production

HEALTHCHECK --interval=10s --timeout=3s --retries=3 \
  CMD curl -f http://localhost:3000/health || exit 1

CMD ["node", "server.js"]
</code></pre>

  <h2>Single-node vs multi-node</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Setup</th>
        <th>Registry driver</th>
        <th>Notes</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Single node</td>
        <td><code>local-transfer</code></td>
        <td>Default. <code>docker save | ssh docker load</code>. No registry needed.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Multi-node (no external registry)</td>
        <td><code>local-registry</code></td>
        <td>Starts ephemeral registry on manager, SSH-tunnels from local to push, all nodes pull from manager's registry.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Multi-node (with external registry)</td>
        <td><code>ghcr</code> or <code>docker-hub</code></td>
        <td>Build and push to external registry; all Swarm nodes pull from there using <code>--with-registry-auth</code>.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</DocsLayout>
